<body>
<p>
Let \(V\) be a vector space.
</p>
<p>
By the universal property of the tensor product, the bilinear map
\[\widetilde\ev:V\times V^*\to\mathbf F\]
given by \((v, \alpha)\mapsto\alpha v\)
induces a unique linear map
\[\ev:V\otimes V^*\to\mathbf F\]
called the <b>evaluation map</b>.
</p>
<p>
The <b>coevaluation map</b>
\[\coev:\mathbf F\to V\otimes V^*\]
is defined to be the dual of the
evaluation map. Explicitly, the coevaluation map is given by
\[\coev(1) = \sum_{i=1}^ne_i\otimes\pi^i\]
and extended linearly,
where \(\{e_i\}_{i=1}^n\) is the standard basis
and \(\{\pi^i\}_{i=1}^n\) is the dual basis.
</p>
<p>
This definition is actually basis-independent.
<details>
<summary>
[explanation]
</summary>
</details>
</p>
<p>
The evaluation and coevaluation maps satisfy
the <a knowl="facts/vec/zigzag">zig-zag identities</a>.
</p>
</body>
</html>
